          <h2>Magnetosphere</h2>
          <p>Neptune possesses a magnetic field similar in strength to Earth's but with an unusual configuration like <a href="/atlas/solar-system/uranus/">Uranus</a>'s. The magnetic field is tilted 47 degrees from Neptune's rotation axis and offset from the planet's center by about 0.55 Neptune radii (about 13,500 km).</p>

          <h3>A Tilted, Offset Field</h3>
          <p>The extreme tilt and offset create a highly asymmetric magnetosphere that wobbles dramatically as Neptune rotates every 16 hours. This configuration, similar to <a href="/atlas/solar-system/uranus/">Uranus</a>, suggests the magnetic field is generated not in a central metallic core but in a conducting fluid layer in the outer parts of the planet's interior—possibly in the water-ammonia "ocean" mantle where ionized molecules can carry electric currents.</p>

          <h3>Magnetospheric Dynamics</h3>
          <p>Neptune's magnetosphere extends about 20-25 Neptune radii on the sunward side but is compressed by the solar wind. On the opposite side, it stretches into a long magnetotail. The wobbling magnetic field creates complex interactions with the solar wind and may contribute to the acceleration of particles that create auroras. Triton contributes to the magnetosphere by releasing neutral particles that become ionized and trapped in Neptune's magnetic field.</p>
        </section>

